- Using the change of base formula we can write

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \text{L.H.S.}&=12\log_{x}2\\[6pt]
  &=12\left(\frac{\log_22}{\log_2x}\right)\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  As $\log_n{n}=1$, we can replace $\log_2{2}$ with 1 and simplify

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &=12\left(\frac{1}{\log_2x}\right)\\[12pt]
  &=\answer{\dfrac{12}{\log_2x}}\hspace{1em}\text{ ...as required}\\[12pt]
  &=\text{R.H.S.}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We can replace $12\log_x2$ with the R.H.S. of the identity from part (a)

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \log_2x&=8-12\log_x2\\[6pt]
  \log_2x&=8-\frac{12}{\log_2x}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We now multiply each side by $\log_2x$ and then rearrange such that the R.H.S. is equal to $0$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  (\log_2x)^2&=8\log_2x-12\\[6pt]
  (\log_2x)^2-8\log_2x+12&=0\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  This is a hidden quadratic equation.  If we replace $\log_2$ with a variable, say $a$, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  a^2-8a+12&=0
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Let's solve this by factorising.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  (a-2)(a-6)&=0    
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore the solutions are

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  a-2&=0&\text{and}&&a-6=0\\[6pt]
  a&=2&&& a=6
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Recall $a=\log_2x$, therefore the solutions become

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \log_2x&=2&&&\log_2x=6\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Converting each to exponential form, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  x&=2^2&&&x=2^6\\[6pt]
  &\hspace{-0.8em}\answer{x=4}&\hspace{0.3em}&&\answer{x=64}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- 14 March 1993 is 20 years after 14 March 1973, therefore $P(20)=50$. We have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  P(20) &= 10e^{20k} \\[8pt]
  50 &= 10e^{20k} \\[8pt]
  e^{20k} &= 5
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Using the numerical solver on the G.D.C. we find that $k\approx 0.08047$. Hence our model is $P(t)=10e^{0.08047t}$.
  14 March 2023 is 50 years after 14 March 1973, hence we calculate $P(50)$:

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  P(50) &= 10e^{0.08047 \times 50} \\[8pt]
  &\hspace{-2.4em}\tcbhighmath{P(50)\approx559}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- If something increases at a constant rate, the compound interest formula applies. Using the formula for compound interest with $PV=10$, $FV=502$, $k=1$ and $n=50$, we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  FV &= PV \times \left(1 + \dfrac{r}{100k}\right)^{kn} \\[8pt]
  502 &= 10 \times \left(1 + \dfrac{r}{100}\right)^{50}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Using the numerical solver on the G.D.C. we find that $\tcbhighmath{r\approx 8.15}$

- Since the initial temperature is $84^\circ$, we obtain

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  T(0) &= A \left(2^{-k(0)}\right) +  B \\[7pt]
  84 &= A + B \hspace{2em}\textcolor{red}{[1]} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Evaluating $T$ at $t=\dfrac{1}{k}$, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  T\left(\dfrac{1}{k}\right) &= A \left(2^{-k/k}\right) +  B \tag*{\textbf{A1}} \\[7pt]
  52 &= \dfrac{A}{2} + B \hspace{2em}\textcolor{red}{[2]} \\[-10pt]
  \end{align*}
  $$

  To find $A$ take the difference $\textcolor{red}{[2]}-\textcolor{red}{[1]}$, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &\hspace{-0.75em} \answer{A = 64}  \\[-10pt]
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Finally, using $\textcolor{red}{[1]}$, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &\hspace{-0.8em} \answer{B = 20} 
  \end{align*}
  $$

- Solving for $k$ in the equation $T(40)=24$, we obtain

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  64 \left(2^{-k(40)}\right) + 20 &= 23 \tag*{\textbf{M1}}\\[7pt]
  &=0.11037...\\[6pt]
  &\hspace{-0.5em}\tcbhighmath{ k = 0.110} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- Solving for $t$, $T(t)=21$, we obtain

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  64 \left( 2^{-0.110t} \right) + 20 &= 21 \tag*{\textbf{M1}}\\[9pt]
  &=54.545...\\[6pt]
  &\hspace{-0.5em}\tcbhighmath{ t = 54.5\,\text{minutes}} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

This model has a fixed value of $k$. In order to use the model we must find $k$.
First, we can find the initial amount of the drug injected into the patient, this occurs when $t=0$

$$
\begin{align*}
D(0)&=240e^{-k(0)}\\[6pt]
D(0)&=240
\end{align*}
$$

Five hours later, $t=5$, we are told that $100\%-65\%=35\%$ of the initial $240\text{ mg}$ remains.
We can use this to find $k$.

$$
\begin{align*}
0.35\times240&=240e^{-5k}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}\\[6pt]
0.35&=e^{-5k}\\[6pt]
\ln{0.35}&=\ln e^{-5k}
\end{align*}
$$

Using the log law $\log_ax^m=m\log_ax$, we get

$$
\begin{align*}
\ln{0.35}&=-5k\ln e
\end{align*}
$$

Since $\ln e=1$, we can simplify the equation and solve for $k$.

$$
\begin{align*}
\ln{0.35}&=-5k\\[6pt]
k&=\frac{\ln{0.35}}{-5}\\[6pt]
&=0.2099\dots\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
\end{align*}
$$

We can now write out the model with out value of $k$

$$
\begin{align*}
    D(t)&=240e^{-0.2099...t}
\end{align*}
$$

We need to find $t$ when the drug remaining in the body is equal to $0.10\times240=24\text{ mg}$.
Hence we need to solve the following equation

$$
\begin{align*}
24&=240e^{-0.2099\dots t}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}
\end{align*}
$$

We can do this graphically by sketching the function $y=D(t)$ and the horizontal line $y=24$
![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/557cb4b2-cf52-4e41-839f-d59ccec63164/images/c8cc79ea-577b-410b-8eae-fb745656bc8d/AA1284.JPEG)


The $x-$coordinate of the intersection point is the solution.
Although a calculator method is preferred, an algebraic approach is also included in case you attempted it that way

$$
\begin{align*}
0.1&=e^{-0.2099\dots t}\\[6pt]
\ln{0.1}&=-0.2099\dots t\\[6pt]
t&=\frac{\ln{0.1}}{-0.2099\dots}\\[6pt]
t&=10.96\dots\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}\\[6pt]
t&=11 \hspace{1em}\text{to the nearest hour}
\end{align*}
$$

Converting the answer to a time we get

$$
\begin{align*}
\text{9:00 + 11 hours = 20:00}
\end{align*}
$$

Therefore the earliest time, to the nearest hour, the patient will be allowed to go home is

$$
\begin{align*}
    \answer{\text{20:00 or 8:00\,pm}}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
\end{align*}
$$

