    Using the formula for the sum of a geometric sequence we can form an equation and then solve for $r$.

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        S_n&=\frac{u_1(1-r^n)}{1-r}\\[12pt]
        S_4&=\frac{u_1(1-r^4)}{1-r}\\[12pt]
        195&=\frac{81(1-r^4)}{1-r}\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Using a G.D.C. we get

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        r&=0.6666...\\[6pt]
        r&=\answer{\dfrac{2}{3}}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

  - Using the answer from (a) (i) and the formula for the sum of the first $n$ terms of a geometric series we can write the general term for $G_n$ as

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        G_n&=\frac{81(1-(\frac{2}{3})^n)}{1-\frac{2}{3}}\\[12pt]
        &=\frac{81(1-(\frac{2}{3})^n)}{\frac{1}{3}}\\[12pt]
        &=81\left(1-\left(\tfrac{2}{3}\right)^n\right)\times3\\[6pt]
        &=\answer{243\left(1-\left(\tfrac{2}{3}\right)^n\right)}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
    \end{align*}
    $$


- In an arithmetic sequence, there is a common difference between terms.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  d&=u_2 - u_1
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Substituting the given values for $u_1$ and $u_2$ we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  d&=\log 48-\log96\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[6pt]
  d&=\log\left(\frac{48}{96}\right)\\[12pt]
  d&=\log \frac{1}{2}\\[12pt]
  d&=\log 2^{-1}\\[6pt]
  d&=\answer{-\log 2}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- The formula for sum of an arithmetic sequence is

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      S_n&=\frac{n}{2}(2u_1+(n-1)d)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Substituting $u_1=\log 96$ and $d=-\log 2$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      A_n&=\frac{n}{2}(2\log 96+(n-1)(-\log 2))\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[6pt]
      &=\frac{n}{2}(\log96^2-(n-1)\log 2)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Applying logarithm rules we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\
  &=\frac{n}{2}(\log96^2-\log2^{(n-1)})\\[12pt]
  &=\frac{n}{2}\log \frac{96^2}{2^{(n-1)}}\\[12pt]
  &=\log\left(\frac{96^2}{2^{(n-1)}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\[12pt]
  &=\log\sqrt{\left(\frac{96^2}{2^{(n-1)}}\right)^n}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[12pt]
  &=\log\left(\frac{\sqrt{96^2}}{\sqrt{2^{(n-1)}}}\right)^n\\[12pt]
  &=\log{\left(\frac{96^n}{(\sqrt{2})^{n^2-n}}\right)}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Looking at the form of the answer we can attempt to rewrite the denominator using by negating its exponent

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &=\log(96^n\times(\sqrt{2})^{n-n^2})
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Let's rewrite $96$ as a product of prime factors

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &=\log((2^5\times3)^n\times(\sqrt{2})^{n-n^2})\tag*{\textbf{M1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Then we'll rewrite $2^5$ as a base of $\sqrt{2}$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &=\log(((\sqrt{2})^{10}\times3)^n\times(\sqrt{2})^{n-n^2})
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Now we can distribute the power of $n$ and then use exponent laws again to simplify to the required form.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &=\log((\sqrt{2})^{10n}\times3^n\times(\sqrt{2})^{n-n^2})\tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[6pt]
  &=\log(3^n\times(\sqrt{2})^{10n+n-n^2})\\[6pt]
  &=\answer{\log(3^n\times(\sqrt{2})^{11n-n^2})}\hspace{3em}\text{as required.}
  \end{align*}
  $$

